# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 10
## Program 10: Demonstrate Auto Scaling Group Concept in Cloud


# Step-by-Step Execution

## Step 1: Verify Existing VPC Resources

Since the VPC resources were already created in previous programs, first verify them.

Go to:
AWS Console → VPC Dashboard

Check the following resources:

VPC: Lab-VPC
CIDR: 10.1.0.0/16

Public Subnet 1: Public-Subnet
CIDR: 10.1.1.0/24

Public Subnet 2: Public-Subnet-2
CIDR: 10.1.2.0/24

Internet Gateway: Lab-IGW

Route Table: Public-RT

The route table should contain:

10.1.0.0/16  → local
0.0.0.0/0    → Lab-IGW

Both public subnets should be associated with Public-RT.

Step 2: Check Security Group

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Security Groups

Open the existing security group:

Lab-SG

Make sure the inbound rules include:

Type: SSH
Protocol: TCP
Port: 22
Source: My IP or 0.0.0.0/0
Type: HTTP
Protocol: TCP
Port: 80
Source: 0.0.0.0/0

HTTP port 80 is required because the Load Balancer forwards browser traffic to EC2 instances.

Step 3: Create Target Group

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Target Groups

Click:

Create target group

Select target type:

Instances

Enter the following details:

Target group name: pg10-target-group
Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
VPC: Lab-VPC
Protocol version: HTTP1

Health check settings:

Health check protocol: HTTP
Health check path: /

Click:

Next

Do not manually select any instance here because the Auto Scaling Group will automatically register instances with the target group.

Click:

Create target group
Step 4: Create Application Load Balancer

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Load Balancers

Click:

Create load balancer

Select:

Application Load Balancer

Click:

Create

Enter basic configuration:

Load balancer name: pg10-alb
Scheme: Internet-facing
IP address type: IPv4

In network mapping, select:

VPC: Lab-VPC

Select both Availability Zones and public subnets:

ap-south-1a → Public-Subnet
ap-south-1b → Public-Subnet-2

In security group section, select:

Lab-SG

In listeners and routing, configure:

Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
Forward to: pg10-target-group

Click:

Create load balancer
Step 5: Create Launch Template

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Launch Templates

Click:

Create launch template

Enter:

Launch template name: pg10-launch-template
Template version description: Auto scaling template for PG10

Choose AMI:

Ubuntu Server

Choose instance type:

t2.micro

or:

t3.micro

Choose key pair:

cloud-lab-key

In network settings:

Do not select a subnet here
Security group: Lab-SG

Important: Do not select a subnet in the Launch Template. The Auto Scaling Group will select the subnets later.

Step 6: Add User Data in Launch Template

In:

Advanced details → User data

Paste the following script:

#!/bin/bash
apt update -y
apt install -y apache2
systemctl start apache2
systemctl enable apache2

HOSTNAME=$(hostname)
PRIVATE_IP=$(hostname -I | awk '{print $1}')

cat > /var/www/html/index.html <<EOF
<html>
<head>
<title>PG-10 Auto Scaling Demo</title>
<style>
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background: #f4f6f8;
    padding: 40px;
}
.card {
    background: white;
    padding: 25px;
    border-radius: 10px;
    width: 70%;
    margin: auto;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px #aaa;
}
h1 {
    color: #232f3e;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="card">
<h1>PG-10: Auto Scaling Group Demo</h1>
<h2>This EC2 instance was launched automatically by Auto Scaling Group</h2>
<p><strong>Hostname:</strong> $HOSTNAME</p>
<p><strong>Private IP:</strong> $PRIVATE_IP</p>
</div>
</body>
</html>
EOF

systemctl restart apache2

Click:

Create launch template

The launch template is now ready.

Step 7: Create Auto Scaling Group

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Auto Scaling Groups

Click:

Create Auto Scaling group

Enter Auto Scaling group name:

pg10-asg

Select launch template:

pg10-launch-template

Click:

Next
Step 8: Select VPC and Subnets

Select the existing VPC:

VPC: Lab-VPC

Select both public subnets:

Public-Subnet
Public-Subnet-2

Click:

Next

The Auto Scaling Group will launch instances inside these selected subnets.

Step 9: Attach Load Balancer

In the load balancing section, select:

Attach to an existing load balancer

Then choose:

Choose from your load balancer target groups

Select:

pg10-target-group

Enable health checks:

Turn on Elastic Load Balancing health checks

Click:

Next
Step 10: Configure Group Size

Set the group size:

Desired capacity: 2
Minimum capacity: 1
Maximum capacity: 3

Meaning:

Desired capacity 2 → Auto Scaling keeps 2 instances running normally.
Minimum capacity 1 → It should not go below 1 instance.
Maximum capacity 3 → It can scale up to 3 instances.

Click:

Next

For this lab, manual desired capacity is enough to demonstrate Auto Scaling Group.

Step 11: Skip Notifications and Add Tag

Notifications:

Skip

Tags are optional.

To identify instances easily, add this tag:

Key: Name
Value: PG10-ASG-Instance

Click:

Next

Review all settings and click:

Create Auto Scaling group
Step 12: Verify Auto Scaling Created Instances

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Instances

After a few minutes, two EC2 instances should be created automatically by the Auto Scaling Group.

They may appear with the name:

PG10-ASG-Instance

Check:

Instance state: Running
Status check: 2/2 checks passed

This proves that the Auto Scaling Group created instances based on desired capacity.

Step 13: Verify Target Group Health

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Target Groups → pg10-target-group → Targets

Wait until both targets show:

Healthy

If they show unhealthy initially, wait 2–3 minutes and refresh.

Step 14: Open Load Balancer DNS

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Load Balancers → pg10-alb

Copy the DNS name of the Load Balancer.

It will look like:

pg10-alb-123456789.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com

Open in browser:

http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME

Expected output:

PG-10: Auto Scaling Group Demo
This EC2 instance was launched automatically by Auto Scaling Group
Hostname: ip-10-1-x-xx
Private IP: 10.1.x.xx

Refresh the browser multiple times. You may see different hostnames or private IP addresses because the Load Balancer sends requests to different Auto Scaling instances.

Demonstrating Auto Scaling Working
Step 15: Terminate One Auto Scaling Instance

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Instances

Select one instance created by Auto Scaling Group.

Click:

Instance state → Terminate instance

Confirm termination.

Step 16: Verify Replacement Instance Is Created

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Auto Scaling Groups → pg10-asg → Activity

You should see activity messages similar to:

Terminating EC2 instance
Launching a new EC2 instance

Now go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Instances

After a few minutes, a new EC2 instance will be created automatically.

This proves that Auto Scaling Group maintains the desired capacity.

Step 17: Check Target Group Again

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Target Groups → pg10-target-group → Targets

Wait until the replacement instance becomes:

Healthy

Open the Load Balancer DNS again:

http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME

The webpage should still open successfully.
